This is a document in the AmigaGuide format.  To read it, use either
AmigaGuide, MultiView, or any other AmigaGuide compatible hypertext
browser.

@node main "AmiPOP"

				@{b}AmiPOP@{ub} - A POP3 Client

				  © 1993 Scott Ellis


    @{" Introduction " link Introduction }
    @{" AmiPOP options " link Options }
    @{" Miscellaneous notes " link MiscellaneousNotes }
    @{" History " link History }

@endnode

@node Introduction "Introduction"

Introduction-

    @{" What it is " link WhatIs }
    @{" What it's not " link WhatNot }
    @{" What you need " link WhatNeed }
    @{" AmiPOP features " link AmiPOPFeatures }

@endnode

@node WhatIs "What it is"
What it is -

	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} is a POP3 Client for AmigaDOS.  It was written directly from
	the POP3 RFC (RFC #1225). @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} is only a simple transport mechanism
	for moving electronic mail messages between a POP-Host, typically
	a mainframe, and your local AmigaDOS system.  The advantage of POP
	over other transports such as SMTP is that all E-mail can still be
	directed to the mainframe system.  This is of primary importance when
	either a dialup line is used, which has a new IP address for each
	connection, or when a user uses many machines, and wishes to be able
	to transparently read mail on all of them.
@endnode

@node WhatNot "What it's not"
What it's not -

	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} is not intended to be a do-everything-mail-reader-reminder-slicer-dicer
	program.  @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} is meant to simply transport mail from a host to your Amiga.
	That's it.  Nothing else.  The "Notify" function inlcuded in @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} is intended
	to be a stopgap measure only, and was included as a request of an especially helpful
	beta-tester.  The "Notify" function will never grow.  If you want to do exotic things
	when you get new mail, use another utility, like Mike Schwarz's 'Mail-Minder', or
	Scott Ellis' (me) program 'Sabot'.
@endnode

@node WhatNeed "What you need"
What you need -

	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} requires either the AS225r2 TCP/IP package or the AmiTCP package, and a
	machine running a POP3 daemon. (More on this later)
	AS225r2 and AmITCP require AmigaDOS 2.0 or higher, and this is therefore required
	by @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} as well.
@endnode

@node AmiPOPFeatures "AmiPOP features"
@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} features -

	· AUISG compliant (or at least it tries to be!)
	· Makes heavy use of 2.0 (and higher) functions such as ReadArgs,
	  utility.library, GadTools, and 2.0 functions in Amiga.lib.
	· Written from RFC 1225, not a port of a Unix or a PC application.
	· Small code size, and low system resource usage.
	· Commodities interface
@endnode

@node Options "Options"
Options -

    @{" Window " link Window }
    @{" Command line " link CommandLine }
@endnode

@node Window "Window"
Window -

    @{" Gadgets " link Gadgets }
    @{" Menus " link Menus }
@endnode

@node Gadgets "Gadgets"
Gadgets -

	Each gadget in the window may be activated from the keyboard by using
	the underlined character in the gadget label (case insensitive).

	Activating a string or integer gadget enables the information to be
	immediately typed in, and the gadget can be de-activated either by
	the RETURN key, or by cycling to the next gadget with the TAB key.

	After activating one of the string or integer gadgets, the TAB key
	allows cycling through each of the gadgets.  The order is:

		· POP Host
		· How Often
		· Username
		· Password
		· Mail Box

	If "How Often" is disabled, then it is ignored, and the gadget is skipped
	during the TAB-Cycle.

	   @{" POP Host " link WPOPHost }
	   @{" Username " link WUsername }
	   @{" Password " link WPassword }
	   @{" Mail Box " link WMailBox }
	   @{" Append to MailBox " link AppendToMailBox }
	   @{" Delete Messages " link DeleteMessages }
	   @{" Check Periodically " link CheckPeriodically }
	   @{" How Often " link HowOften }
	   @{" Check Now " link CheckNow }
@endnode

@node WPOPHost "POPHost"
POP Host -

	This is the address of the machine which is running the
	POP3 daemon.  It can either be an IP address, a full
	name and domain, or just the name (if the site is in
	your inet:DB/Hosts file, or in your local domain).
@endnode

@node WUsername "Username"
Username -

	Username is your login name on the POP Host machine.
	It is used in determining which mailbox to look at,
	and which password to accept.
@endnode

@node WPassword "Password"
Password -

	This is the password for Username on machine POP Host.
	The Password gadget is a special string gadget which
	ill NOT echo what you type.  Instead, you will see
	a bullet ( "·" ) for each character you type.  The
	Password gadget is more limited in it's editing abilities
	then the other gadget, and will only allow you to delete
	characters from the end of the password, or clear the
	entire gadget.
@endnode

@node WMailBox "Mail Box"
Mail Box -

	Mail Box is the FULL AmigaDOS path and filename that
	you would like the mail stored in on your Amiga.
	Most UUCP mail-readers require this be "UUMAIL:Username",
	but you are free to choose whatever you like.
@endnode

@node AppendToMailBox "Append to Mail Box"
Append to Mail Box -

	When checked, this gadget will append all incoming mail
	to the file listed in the MailBox gadget.  If it is
	unchecked, new mail will overwrite the mailbox.  This
	gadget is most useful in conjuction with the "Delete
	Messages" gadget.
@endnode

@node DeleteMessages "Delete Messages"
Delete Messages -

	If Delete Messages is checked, it will delete the mail
	message on POP Host after it is downloaded.  Caution
	is advised with this gadget, since once mail is deleted
	on the POP Host, there is no way to retrieve it.
	This gadget is best used with "Append to MailBox".
@endnode

@node CheckPeriodically "Check Periodically"
Check Periodically -

	When this gadget is marked, mail will be transfered
	from the POP Host on a time schedule.  This schedule
	is defined in "How Often".
@endnode

@node HowOften "How Often"
How Often -

	This gadget defines the number of minutes that should
	elapse between queries for mail to POP Host.  If
	Check Periodically is not checked, this gadget will
	be disabled, and have no effect.
@endnode

@node CheckNow "Check Now"
Check Now -

	Check Now will immediately query POP Host for mail.
	It is primarily used for impatient people who cannot
	wait for the Check Periodically time to elapse, or
	who would like the mail checked manually, instead
	of periodically.
@endnode

@node Menus "Menus"
Menus -

	Menu options can also be accessed via their key combination (Right Amiga key).

	    @{" Hide " link Hide }
	    @{" About... " link About }
	    @{" Quit " link Quit }
@endnode

@node Hide
Hide -

	This option will close the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window, but not quit
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui}.  The window may be reopened either via the
	hotkey (If specified) or with Commodities Exchange.
@endnode

@node About "About..."
About... -

	Opens a requester with the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} authors name.
@endnode

@node Quit "Quit"
Quit -

	Quits the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} program.  This is identical to
	sending @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} a Control-C character, or clicking
	on the close box in the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node CommandLine "Command Line"
Command Line -

	Command line options maybe be given either on the command line
	when starting @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} from a shell, or as ToolTypes when
	using @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} from an icon.

	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} uses ReadArgs to process command line and tooltype
	arguments passed to it.

        Arguments:

            @{" Username " link Username}
            @{" Password " link Password}
            @{" POPHost " link POPHost}
            @{" MailDir " link MailDir}
            @{" CheckPer " link CheckPer}
            @{" Time " link Time}
            @{" Delete " link Delete}
            @{" Append " link Append}
            @{" NoWindow " link NoWindow}
            @{" Port " link Port}
            @{" Notify " link Notify}
            @{" Cx_Popkey " link Cx_Popkey}
            @{" Immediate " link Immediate}
            @{" Quiet " link Quiet}
            @{" PubScreen " link PubScreen}
            @{" Once " link Once}
@endnode

@node Username "Username"
Username -

	This is identical to the Username gadget in the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.  Specifying a username on the
	command line avoids having to enter it into the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node Password "Password"
Password -

	This is identical to the Password gadget in the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.  Specifying a password on the
	command line avoids having to enter it into the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node POPHost "POPHost"
POPHost -

	This is identical to the POP Host gadget in the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.  Specifying a POP Host on the
	command line avoids having to enter it into the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node MailDir "MailDir"
MailDir -

	This is identical to the MailBox gadget in the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.  Specifying a MailBox on the
	command line avoids having to enter it into the
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node CheckPer "CheckPer"
CheckPer -

	When given, this switch specifies that the
	Check Periodically function should be enabled.  It
	is identical to making Check Periodically enabled
	in the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node Time "Time"
Time -

	Time, followed by an integer will place a default
	value into the How Often gadget in the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui}
	window.  If CheckPer is not also given, or if the
	Check periodically gadget in the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window is
	not active, this setting has no effect.
@endnode

@node Delete "Delete"
Delete -

	When present, this switch enables the Delete Messages
	function of @{i}AmiPOP@{ui}.  It is identical to the Delete
	Messages gadget in the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node Append "Append"
Append -

	When present, Append activates the Append to MailBox
	feature of @{i}AmiPOP@{ui}.  It is identical to activating the
	Append to MailBox gadget in the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window.
@endnode

@node NoWindow "NoWindow"
NoWindow -

	When the NoWindow flag is given, it instructs @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} not
	to open it's window my default.  This is useful when
	running @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} from WBStartup, or from a script.
	The @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} window may later be opened by the hotkey, or
	via Commodities Exchange.
@endnode

@node Port "Port"
Port -

	Normally, POP3 uses port 110 on the POP Host machine.
	When the Port switch is given, followed by an integer,
	that will be used in attempts to connect to the POP3
	daemon on the POP Host, instead of port 110.
@endnode

@node Notify "Notify"
Notify -

	The Notify switch will force @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} to open a requester
	when it detects that you have new mail.  By default,
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} does not notify the user of new mail.
@endnode

@node Cx_Popkey
Cx_Popkey -

	This is the hotkey that @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} will use.  When pressed,
	@{i}AmiPOP@{ui} will open it's window, if it is not already open.
	Any valid hotkey combination may be given.  If Cx_Popkey
	is not specified, @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} will not add itself to the
	input chain, and will not cause any system performance
	decrease.
@endnode

@node Immediate
Immediate -

	The Immediate switch causes @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} to immediately check for mail when
	it is started.  The default is to wait the ammount of time specified in
	the "How Often" gadget befor checking.
@endnode

@node Quiet
Quiet -

	When the Quiet flag is given to @{i}AmiPOP@{ui}, @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} will not open
	any requesters.  This means that you will not be able to get any notice of
	errors, or get the Notify or About requesters.
@endnode

@node PubScreen "PubScreen"
PubScreen -

	Giving @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} the name of a public screen will cause the @{i}AmiPOP@{ui}
	window to open on that public screen.  If @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} cannot open on the
	specified screen, or if no screen is specified, @{i}AmiPOP@{ui} will open on
	the default public screen (normally WorkBench).
@endnode

@node Once "Once"
Once -

	The "Once" keyword causes AmiPOP to check for mail immediately, then exit.
@endnode

@node MiscellaneousNotes "Miscellaneous Notes"
Miscellaneous Notes -

	@{" Pop3 Daemon " link POP3Daemon}
	@{" Cautions " link Cautions}
	@{" Quitting AmiPOP " link Quitting}
	@{" Thanks " link Thanks}
	@{" Bugs " link Bugs}
